{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"21aa233e-bbad-47d2-9bec-4627d0925033","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft Testing Platform natively. Filter by class with `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe tree-node path format is `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Method`, so `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches any assembly and namespace, the `SmsNotificationTests` class, and all its test methods. The `--` separates `dotnet run` args from the test app args.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a9b07972-66d8-41b0-9689-929d4f99ac47","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120) using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. TUnit uses MTP's filter syntax, not VSTest's `--filter`.\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, to filter by class name, the syntax is:\n\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nor using the `--filter-class` option:\n\n```\ndotnet run --filter-class SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The project has `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` which is typical for MTP-based test projects.\n\n\nThe treenode filter format for MTP follows the pattern `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Method`, so filtering by class would use something like `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` to match any method within that class.","outputTokens":591},"id":"a2daba34-f74e-4877-b86a-3e73efc67f3b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:32:05.009Z","parentId":"fd192860-b286-4d65-881b-60c6ba8f4ad3"}
